 His colleague Major Thomas J  Jackson  was placed in command of the artillery two howitzers manned by 21 cadets   less than two years after the duty at Charles Town  Jackson would acquire the nickname  Stonewall  and would soon thereafter achieve fame as one of the Confederacy s ablest military leaders  The VMI cadets reached Charles Town on November 26th and were relieved from duty on December 6th  They returned to Lexington via Richmond  where they were greeted by the Governor and members of the Virginia Assembly  List of cadets on duty at the execution Letters to Virginia s Governor Henry A  Wise concerning the readiness of cadets  VMI Orders relating to the cadets at Charles Town  Eyewitness account  Letter from VMI Professor Thomas J  Jackson  later known as  Stonewall  to his wife  describing the execution  Jackson was in charge of the cadet artillery contingent  Eyewitness account  Letter from John T  L  Preston  one of the VMI officers present at Charles Town  Summary report of Superintendent Francis H  Smith  January 16  1860   Related Collection  Francis H  Smith Armory Commission Letters  VMI Foundation Keydet Club Alumni Webcams Directories My VMI  RESOURCES   Title IX  Health   Safety   IT   Site Index Parents   Families   Cadets   Non discrimination Statement   Privacy   THE VMI PHILOSOPHY The VMI experience is framed by relevant education within a military environment  It s an education that develops character  fosters a lifelong appreciation of physical fitness engenders a sense of responsibility to others  and cultivates the ability to master adversity  VIRGINIA MILITARY INSTITUTE Lexington  Virginia 24450 General Information   540  464 7230  Admissions  admissions vmi edu John Brown Execution  1859   VMI Cadet Guard   Online Resources from the VMI Archives       John Brown Execution  1859   VMI Cadet Guard   Online Resources from the VMI Archives                     skip to content All Collections Limit to Historical Rosters Limit to Photographs V